      "x`. So `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = ∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹`.\n\nBut Lean does not automatically simplify `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` to `∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹`. So the goal is to show that if `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`, then `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`.\n\nBut looking closely at the Lean goal, the hypothesis is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`, and the goal is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`. \n\nBut notice that `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` in Lean is `((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹`, which is just `∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹`, because `(a⁻¹)⁻¹ = a` for any `a : ℝ≥0∞` with `a ≠ 0`. So `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = ∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹`. \n\nThe issue is that in Lean, the hypothesis and the goal use different forms of the sum. In Lean, `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` is notation for `∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹`, whereas the hypothesis is written as `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`, but `p x : ℕ → ℝ≥0`, so `(p x)⁻¹` would be `(p x : ℝ≥0)⁻¹`. But in the context of `ENNReal`, this is the same because coercions are happening. \n\nBut perhaps Lean can automatically recognize that `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`, assuming that `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) ≠ 0`. \n\nBut if `s.Nonempty`, then because `p x ≠ 0`, `(p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`, and the sum of non-zero `ENNReal` is non-zero. \n\nAlternatively, we can notice that Lean's hypothesis is not correctly stating what it should, because it uses `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` instead of `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`, but it was just supposed to be the same as `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`.\n\nBut in Lean's theorem statement, `hpq` is `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (↑q)⁻¹`. \n\nHowever, we need to understand that `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)` is `ENNReal`, and for any non-zero `x : ENNReal`, `x⁻¹⁻¹ = x`. \n\nBut in Lean, `x⁻¹⁻¹ = x`, because if `x : ENNReal`, then `x ≠ 0`, and `(x⁻¹)⁻¹ = x`.\n\nThus, we can simplify `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = ∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹`.\n\nBut we need to check if `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) ≠ 0`. \n\nBut if `s.Nonempty`, then `∃ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`, and `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) ≠ 0`, because `p x : ℝ≥0`, and `p x ≠ 0` implies `(p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`.\n\nBut what if `s = ∅`? \n\nBut in the given code, we have `hs✝ : (cons i s hi).Nonempty`, and `hs : s.Nonempty`, so `s` is not empty. \n\nThus, `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) ≠ 0`, because there exists at least one `x ∈ s` such that `(p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`.\n\nTherefore, in Lean, we have `((∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)`.\n\nBut we need to write this in Lean. \n\n### Simplest Lean Proof Idea\n\nThe simplest way to prove this is to:\n\n1. Recognize that `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞) ≠ 0`.\n2. Use the property that for any `x : ℝ≥0∞`, `x ≠ 0`, we have `x⁻¹⁻¹ = x`.\n3. Substitute to get `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)`.\n\nIn Lean, step 1 is done by noting that if `s.Nonempty`, then there exists some `x ∈ s` such that `(p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`, so the sum is not zero.\n\n### Step 1: Show `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞) ≠ 0`\n\nBecause `s.Nonempty`, there exists some `x ∈ s`. Since `p x ≠ 0`, `(p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`, and thus `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞) ≥ (p x)⁻¹ > 0`.\n\n### Step 2: Use `x⁻¹⁻¹ = x`\n\nFor any `x : ℝ≥0∞`, `x ≠ 0`, we have `(x⁻¹)⁻¹ = x`.\n\n### Step 3: Simplify the Goal\n\nTherefore, `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)`.\n\n### Proof of `x⁻¹⁻¹ = x` in Lean\n\nIn Lean, `x : ℝ≥0∞`, and if `x ≠ 0`, then `x⁻¹ ≠ 0`, and `(x⁻¹)⁻¹ = x`.\n\n### Applying It to the Sum\n\nThe sum is non-zero because `s.Nonempty` and `(p x)⁻¹ > 0` for each `x`.\n\n### Formal Proof Sketch\n\n1. Since `s.Nonempty`, there exists `x ∈ s`.\n2. Show `(p x)⁻¹ ≠ 0`.\n3. Show `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) ≠ 0`.\n4. Use the fact that for `y : ℝ≥0∞`, `y ≠ 0` implies `y⁻¹⁻¹ = y`.\n5. Conclude that the LHS of `hpq` becomes `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) = (q)⁻¹`.\n6. But we need to adjust the goal to have `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹`, not `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`.\n\nBut in Lean, `∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ = ∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹`, just a renaming.\n\nThus, we can write:\n\n`(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`.\n\nBut our goal is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`, but we have `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`.\n\nThus, we need to either:\n\n1. Simplify `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`.\n2. Or re-express `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹` in terms of `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`.\n\nBut `∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ = ∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹` because it's the same sum. \n\nBut perhaps Lean doesn't know that `∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹ = ∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹`? \n\nActually, Lean does, because `x` and `i` are bound variables.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)` is the same as `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)`? \n\nYes, they are the same sum, just with different bound variable names.\n\nThus, we can directly use `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)` to simplify the hypothesis and match the goal.\n\n### Conclusion\n\n1. Since `s.Nonempty`, `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) ≠ 0`.\n2. Therefore, `((∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`.\n3. Substitute into `hpq` to get `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) = (q)⁻¹`.\n4. But `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)`, so we can rewrite the LHS of the goal in terms of this.\n5. However, the goal has `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹`, not `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)`, which complicates things.\n\nWait a minute! The issue is that the hypothesis is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`, but the goal is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`. \n\nBut `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`, so `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)`. \n\nBut we need to show `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`.\n\nHmm, it seems like there is no direct relation unless `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹`, which doesn't make sense unless `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) = 1`, but that is not given.\n\nThis suggests that the hypothesis does not directly imply the goal. \n\nBut perhaps in the actual mathematical context, the statement was not correctly translated to Lean. \n\nIn particular, perhaps the intended hypothesis was `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹) = (q)⁻¹`, and we should have `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹` in the goal.\n\nBut let's look carefully at the problem again.\n\nIn Lean, the statement to prove is `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (p x)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹ → (p i)⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (q)⁻¹`.",
