      "a`.\n\nTherefore:\n`(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = ∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹`.\n\nThus, the hypothesis `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (↑q)⁻¹` is the same as `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + ∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹ = (↑q)⁻¹`.\n\nAnd we want to prove `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (↑q)⁻¹`, but `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = ∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹`.\n\nThus, both sides are equal, and the result follows.\n\nBut we need to formalize that `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = ∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹`.\n\nWe do this as follows:\n1. `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal) : ℝ≥0∞ = ∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹`.\n   - By `NNReal.coe_sum`, then `NNReal.coe_inv`.\n2. Thus, `((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞) = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹)⁻¹`.\n3. Therefore, `((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹)`.\n\nBut in Lean, we have `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` vs `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹`, and we need to show that `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹)⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)`.\n\nBut in Lean:\n- `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` is `(∑ x ∈ s, (p x : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹)`.\n- `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` is `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i : NNReal)⁻¹)` (as `NNReal`).\n- Then `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal) : ℝ≥0∞ = ∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹` because `(p i : NNReal)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞ = (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹` and `NNReal.coe_sum`.\n\nThus, `((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal)⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹)`, because:\n1. `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal) : ℝ≥0∞ = ∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹`.\n2. Taking inverses: `((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹ : NNReal) : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹)⁻¹`.\n3. Taking inverses again: `((∑ i ∈ s, (p",
