      "(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)`.\n\nBut our goal is to show that `(p i)⁻¹ + (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (q : ℝ≥0∞)⁻¹`. \n\nBut `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` in `NNReal`, and `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` as an element of `ℝ≥0∞`.\n\nTherefore, in Lean's notation, if we coerce `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` to `ℝ≥0∞`, then it is the same as `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)`, and then `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` because it is non-zero. \n\nBut in Lean, `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` is `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` in `NNReal`.\n\nHowever, in `hpq`, the term `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹` is actually `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` in `ℝ≥0∞`.\n\nBut when we write `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹)` in Lean, it is interpreted as `(↑((∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹))`, but `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)` in `NNReal`. So `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ : ℝ≥0∞)` is `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹) : ℝ≥0∞)` = `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)`.\n\nThus, in `hpq`, we have `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (↑q)⁻¹`, and in the goal `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹) = (↑q)⁻¹`.\n\nBut since `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` and `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹))` are the same, and `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` because it is not zero, and similarly `(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)`, so coercing to `ℝ≥0∞` gives the same result. \n\nHence, `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` and similarly `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹) = (↑(p i))⁻¹ + (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹))`, but these are equal because `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) = (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹))`.\n\nThis seems to mean that in fact `hpq` is `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹) = (↑q)⁻¹`, but we need to get `(↑(p i))⁻¹ + (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹) = (↑q)⁻¹`.\n\nBut as we saw earlier, `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` and `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹) = (↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹))`, and these two are equal.\n\nBut let me double check:\nWe have `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)⁻¹⁻¹ = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` because `(∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` is not zero (the sum is positive because `s` is nonempty and each term is positive).\n\nNow, `(↑(∑ i ∈ s, (p i)⁻¹)) = (∑ x ∈ s, (↑(p x))⁻¹)` because the coercion of a sum is the sum of coercions.\n\nThus, `(↑",
